<br>
Astronomers are trying to find places in the solar system and beyond where conditions are right for life. Thus far, more than 80 planets have been discovered orbiting distant stars, but all are forbidding and unlike earth. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/10/02 6:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=93.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/alien.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Astronomers launch search for Earth-like planets.</span><hr size=1> I have a problem with that estimate.  It makes too many assumptions. <br>
All extrasolar planets discovered to date have been inferred, not<br>
directly observed. I questioned one of the discoverers once when he<br>
claimed that one massive planet many times the size of Jupiter was<br>
discovered orbiting a distant sun.  How did he know it was one planet,<br>
instead of several smaller planets that combined created a similar<br>
wobble effect?  His reply was that he didn't know if it was indeed one<br>
planet.  It could be several planets.  So basically, until these<br>
extrasolar planets can be directly observed, we won't know the exact<br>
number orbiting any given star.  Thus, we don't know the distance that<br>
these alien worlds orbit their sun from.  In other words, there may<br>
have been an Earth type (Class M if you're a Star Trek fan) planet<br>
orbiting one of the systems already observed to possess plantary<br>
bodies.  Too many assumptions with today's technology. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1127<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/10/02 10:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=93.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Astronomers launch search for Earth-like planets.</span><hr size=1> Small Earthlike planets or smaller wouldnt make a noticable wobble effect on their parent star. Not unless there were enough of them to equal several Jupiters. Jupiter is more massive than everything else in our system combined (excluding the sun ofcourse). That would mean an awful lot of planetary mass, all on the same side of the Star, and orbiting at speeds which keep them so aligned. A bit of a long shot I think.<br>
I agree that the objects arent massive planets. More like brown dwarfs. Proto-stars. Some distinction should be made between gas giants and baby stars. There probably is one but I dont know what it is. When an object is nearly a star and closer to nuclear ignition than it is to being a terrestrial planet it should possibly be called a 'wannabe star'.  <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
